Here's a complete migration guide. The original code has several constructs that are broken or removed in .NET 8.

## Breaking Changes & Pitfalls

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Severity |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | 🔴 Build runs, crashes at runtime |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works but unreliable for `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | 🟡 May hang on shutdown |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | Replace with `Channel<T>` | 🟡 Original has a race condition — multiple enqueues, one dequeue per signal |
| Raw `Thread` | `Task.Run` + `CancellationToken` | 🟡 Modernization |

## Race condition in the original

If two calls to `Enqueue` happen before `RunLoop` wakes, `Set()` is called twice on an already-signaled event — the second signal is lost, leaving one item stranded in the queue.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _worker;

    public void Start()
    {
        _worker = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* graceful shutdown */ }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        if (_worker is not null)
            await _worker;
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Key differences

1. **`Channel<T>`** replaces `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` — it's thread-safe, async-native, and handles backpressure. No lost signals.
2. **`CancellationToken`** replaces `Thread.Abort()`/`Interrupt()` — cooperative cancellation that works everywhere in .NET 8.
3. **`Channel.Writer.Complete()`** provides graceful drain — the worker finishes all queued items before exiting, unless the hard cancellation timeout fires.
4. **`IAsyncDisposable`** ensures cleanup via `await using`.

## Usage

```csharp
await using var processor = new EventProcessor();
processor.Start();
processor.Enqueue("event-1");
processor.Enqueue("event-2");
await processor.StopAsync(); // drains queue, then stops
```

## If you need a synchronous API (drop-in replacement)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    _channel.Writer.Complete();
    _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    _worker?.GetAwaiter().GetResult(); // blocks; avoid in async contexts
    _cts.Dispose();
}
```

Use the async version wherever possible — the sync fallback risks deadlocks in UI/ASP.NET contexts.
